- Followed preprocess -> anomaly detection -> fault identification -> root cause localization using metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv. We computed global thresholds (P95) per (cmdb_id,kpi) and per (cmdb_id,trace_name), filtered to the 2022-03-20 08:30–09:00 window, detected anomalies, aggregated anomalies to components, and correlated traces and logs. Key evidence: 
  * Window A (early window around 08:30–08:36): checkoutservice pods (checkoutservice-0/1/2) show earliest anomalous timestamps at 2022-03-20 08:30:00 (UTC+8) and very large aggregated anomaly counts; checkoutservice-1 shows the largest deviation (max_severity ≈ 405×). Focused trace instances show latency spikes on the checkout → currency → shipping call chain (duration_p95/duration_mean spikes between ~08:32–08:36 with severity up to ~4.6×). Mesh/istio network KPIs related to checkout paths also show extremely high severity. Node-level TCP retransmissions were also observed in the metric scan. Together this indicates an inter-service/network problem rooted around checkoutservice interactions starting at 08:30:00. 
  * Window B (later window around 08:48–08:52): all frontend pods (frontend-0/1/2 and frontend2-0) show correlated anomalies: trace.self.error_rate and trace anomalies with earliest timestamps at 2022-03-20 08:48:00 (UTC+8), log.error_count > 0 first appearing at 08:48:00, and concentrated error_logs with warning messages (“failed to retrieve...”) between 08:48:52–08:51:53. All three frontend pods present errors, so the service-level frontend is implicated. Metrics and traces show the frontends experiencing elevated error rates and some increased downstream latencies at the same time. 
- How the root-cause decisions were made: per the diagnosis rules, we (1) used metrics first to narrow candidates, (2) used traces to choose the most-downstream faulty service when multiple service-level faults were present, and (3) used logs to confirm exact occurrence times and error symptoms. For Window A, checkoutservice had the earliest and most severe metric anomalies and traces show checkout→downstream latency — making checkoutservice the most likely root cause. For Window B, frontends (all pods) simultaneously exhibit trace and log errors beginning at 08:48:00, so the frontend service is the root cause for the second failure. 
- Uncertainties and caveats: many error_rate traces have global P95==0 which overflags any non-zero errors; we treated those flags cautiously and relied on combined evidence (trace numeric severity, metric severity, and error_logs) to conclude. Currency/shipping component-level aggregates were NA in one component-level table, but direct trace instance values show they experienced elevated latency during Window A — consistent with propagation from the checkout path. 

